87":"1187","1174":"1174","about 1187":"about 1187","Willey, Salop, Shropshire, England":"Willey, Shropshire, England","of Willey, Shropshire, England":"Willey, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"WILLEY","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a pet form of the personal name   Will  , a short form of   William  . In some instances a variant of   Wiley  .","Americanized form of Swiss German   Willi  .","History: Isaac Willey is recorded in Boston, MA, in 1640, and went on to be one of the founders of New London, CT. His descendent Samuel Hopkins Willey (1821–1914) was one of the founders of the College of California at Berkeley in 1860."],"variants":[{"name":"Willie","meanings":["English: variant of   Willey  .","Scottish: variant of   Wylie  .","Native American (e.g. Navajo and Seminole): adoption of the English personal name <i>Willie</i> (pet form of   William  ) as a surname."]},{"name":"Will","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Will</i>, a short form of   William  . This surname is now commonly found in Scotland, in Aberdeenshire, Angus, and Kincardineshire.","English: topographic name for someone who lived by a spring or stream, from Middle English <i>wel</i>, <i>wel(l)e</i>, <i>wille</i>, in a southwestern dialect form. This surname is found predominantly in the south and southwestern parts of the country. Compare   Well   1.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>iwil</i>, <i>wil(l)e</i> ‘agreeable, pleasing’."]},{"name":"Willy","meanings":["English: variant of   Willey  .","Americanized form of German   Willi  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]},{"name":"Mrs","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Latin <i>Ursus</i> ‘bear’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":28,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":37,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":72,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William De Mrs WILLEY was born about 1187, in Willey, Shropshire, England. She had at least 1 son with William De Willey."},"et":{"about 1187–":"umbes 1187–Surnud","1174–Male":"1174–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1187–Female":"1187–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1187":"1187","1174":"1174","about 1187":"umbes 1187","Willey, Salop, Shropshire, England":"Willey, Shropshire, England","of Willey, Shropshire, England":"Willey, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1187–":"noin 1187–Kuollut","1174–Male":"1174–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1187–Female":"1187–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1187":"1187","1174":"1174","about 1187":"noin 1187","Willey, Salop, Shropshire, England":"Willey, Shropshire, England","of Willey, Shropshire, England":"Willey, Shropshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1187–":"environ 1187–Décédée","1174–Male":"1174–Décédé","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1187–Female":"1187–Décédée","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1187":"1187","1174":"1174","about 1187":"environ 1187","Willey, Salop, Shropshire, England":"Willey, Shropshire, Angleterre","of Willey, Shropshire, England":"Willey, Shropshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William De Mrs WILLEY est née environ 1187, à Willey, Shropshire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec William De Willey."},"de":{"about 1187–":"um 1187–Verstorben","1174–M